name: 1 Finsbury Avenue
description: 1 Finsbury Avenue is a Grade II listed building constructed in the early 1980s by Arup Associates (Peter Foggo). As the first building in the Broadgate development it was significant in defining the speculative office typology in London.

name: 38 Grosvenor Square
description: A beautiful Mayfair town house c 1727 original to the Square. Transformed 1776 by John Johnson for Duke of Dorset; magnificent staircase, lavish ‘Adamesque’ entertaining suite. Mid-C19 Italianate front by Thomas Cundy.

name: A River's Tale. A guided walk along the Thames Path
description: For about an hour and a half we will walk along the Thames Path from Millennium Bridge  finishing at the old Billingsgate Fish Market along the way learning of the prosperity, power, prestige and plague this great river has brought us

name: A Ruskinian Walk Through Shared Heritage
description: Ruskinian walk from RIBA award-winning Chiswick Business Park, Gunnersbury Triangle Nature Reserve through South Acton Estate, birthplace of artist Patrick Caulfield; Woodlands Park Ice House; to home of Wm Willett, of Daylight Saving Time
address: Chiswick Business Park, 566, Chiswick High Road , W4 5YA

name: Abbey Mills Pumping Station
description: Abbey Mills pumping station 'A', built by engineer Joseph Bazalgette, Edmund Cooper and architect Charles Driver. Built between 1865 and 1868 it has been described as the cathedral of sewage.

name: Airport House, Historic Croydon Airport
description: Unique Grade II* listed 1928 Government building in restrained neoclassical style. Britain's first intercontinental airport terminal. Landmark building featuring the world's oldest Air Traffic Control Tower. Upgraded to Grade II* in 2017.

name: Alderman Jones House
description: Becontree Estate two storey cottage house with garden located on a banjo.

name: All Saints Carshalton
description: 12C south aisle and former chancel. Blomfield nave, chancel, baptistry. Kempe glass, Bodley reredos and screen, spectacular Comper decorations, monuments and brasses, award-winning lighting scheme, fine modern benches.

name: All Saints Church (The Old Church)
description:
Original parish church of Chingford, with Norman foundations and interesting monuments.
Tudor porch.

name: All Saints Church, Edmonton
description: Church dating back to at least early C12. Charles and Mary Lamb are buried in the churchyard.

name: All Saints, Foots Cray
description: Medieval church (c1330) amended 1863 by Hakewill and retaining original elements such as windows and an arch to the north aisle, and altar tomb of Sir Simon de Vaughan.

name: Amelia Street
description: A new Peabody housing development of 55 homes to rent and buy and ground floor commercial space. All of the homes are dual aspect, with large private balconies and terraces as well as access to a landscaped communal garden.

name: Ancient Livery Companies in the City of London
description: Ancient Livery Companies of the City of London

name: Architecture and Art in the City
description: Architecture and Art in the City

name: BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir
description: Europe’s first traditional Hindu temple is a masterpiece of exquisite Indian craftsmanship. Using 5,000 tonnes of Italian and Indian marble and the finest Bulgarian limestone, it was hand-carved in India before being assembled in London.

name: Baitul Futuh Mosque
description: Largest purpose-built mosque in Western Europe accommodating 13,000 worshippers. The building is a blend of Islamic and modern British architecture and incorporates much of the structure of an old dairy site.
address: Ahmadiyya Muslim Association, 181 London Road, Morden, SM4 5PT

name: Baker Street Complex
description: In 1863, Baker Street was one of the stations on the world's first subterranean metro line. The Metropolitan Railway developed the area around the station to incorporate offices and even residential flats. This tour explores that history.

name: Barking Riverside London
description: A new sustainable neighbourhood being created alongside 2km of south-facing Thames river frontage. A partnership with The Mayor of London and L&Q, 10,800 new homes will house up to 29,000 people.
address: The Wilds at Barking Riverside, Northgate Road, Barking, IG11 0AN

name: Barts Pathology Museum, Queen Mary University of London
description: Barts Pathology Museum is based in the grounds of St Bartholomews Hospital at West Smithfield and houses over 4,000 medical specimens on display over 3 mezzanine levels of the Victorian museum.
address: 3rd Floor Robin Brook Centre, St Bartholomew's Hospital, West Smithfield, EC1A 7BE

name: Battersea's Hidden Parks
description: Walking tour introducing nine smaller local parks and public gardens, and revealing their history. Led by Clare Graham, Chair of the Society's Open Spaces Committee and author of 'Discovering Battersea's Open Spaces: a walking guide'.

name: Bedford Park Walking Tour
description: Bedford Park is a planned suburb of 1877-86 and a precursor to the Garden Cities and Garden Suburbs. You'll see houses, churches, and public houses by leading 19th century architects Richard Norman Shaw, EW Godwin, EJ May, Maurice B Adams.

name: Benjamin Franklin House
description: Grade I listed Georgian house, the only surviving home of Benjamin Franklin, retaining many original features including central staircase, lathing, 18th Century panelling, stoves, windows, fittings and beams.

name: Bevin Court
description: One of London's hidden Modernist gems. Lubetkin's motto 'Nothing is too good for ordinary people' resonates through this building.

name: Blackbook Winery
description: Blackbook Winery is in a converted Victorian railway arch.  It is open plan, with all equipment required to process, ferment and age wine on site – press, tanks, barrels etc.  Our grapes come from English growers within 2 hours of London.
address: Arch 41, London Stone Business Estate, Broughton Street, SW8 3QR

name: Blackheath Society Historic Walk, Blackheath SE3
description: Neil Rhind will lead this historic walk along the north and east side of the Heath.

name: Bluebell Centre, Perivale Wood Nature Reserve
description: The low carbon building is a straw bale construction built on compacted tyres with a cedar roof.  In the Perivale Nature Reserve owned by the Selborne Society it is used for society meeting and as an education centre for adults and schools.

name: Blythe House and Olympia
description: Blythe House is an amazing full-on late Victorian design for the Post-Office Savings Bank. Olympia is a major exhibition venue in west London. The walk will also cover the former Joseph Lyons' factory Cadby Hall.
address: Meeting point Olympia Station, Overground and District line, Hammersmith Road,, W14 8UX

name: Bow Baptist Church
description: Bow Baptist Church has met on its current site near Bow Bridge since at least 1785. It currently occupies a purpose built ground floor of a multi-storey residential building completed in 2012.

name: Bow Church – St Mary
description: Medieval village church, restored in late 19C and after bomb damage in WWII. 15C font and memorials from five centuries. Grade II* listed. Refurbished for 700th anniversary in 2011; the bell tower and cupola were restored in 2017-18.

name: Branch Place, Colville Estate
description:
Contemporary public housing for Hackney Council. 
Two medium-rise, brick-built urban buildings of 116 mixed-tenure homes with landscaped communal spaces and a revised street network.

Zoom meeting link: https://bit.ly/36N9PKo

name: Brentford Canal Toll House and Gauging Lock
description: Single-storey canal toll house (1911) where tolls were collected for passing through the lock. Grand Junction Canal connected the Thames at Brentford to the Industrial Midlands in 1794 at the height of the industrial revolution.
address: Access off High Street, Brentford, TW8 8EE

name: Brentham Garden Suburb
description: Britain's first co-partnership garden suburb, first houses built 1901. Parker and Unwin's plan introduced 1907, mainly Arts and Crafts style; fascinating social history.
address: The Brentham Club, 38 Meadvale Road, W5 1NP

name: Brockley 3 Peaks Walk
description: A circular 5 mile walk, mainly through parkland with beautiful views across London from the 3 peaks – Hilly Fields, Blythe Hill Fields and One Tree Hill.  The walk is easy to moderately difficult. One Tree Hill is not wheelchair friendly.
address: Pistachios in the Park, Hilly Fields, Brockley, SE4 1LB

name: Brockley's Historic Mews
description: Brockley Conservation Area's quirky mews are a mixture of leafy lanes and industrial units, with Victorian and interesting modern architecture existing in harmony. The cherished public right of way  allows community contact with nature.
address: Ashby, Wickham, Breakspears Mews, Junctions with Ashby Road, SE4 1TF

name: Bruce Castle Museum
description: Tudor Manor House built for Sir William Compton in 1514, substantially altered in 17C, 18C & 19C. A museum since 1906 housing local history and community collections, archives, art & exhibitions of Bruce Castle, and Haringey area.
address: Bruce Castle Museum,, Lordship Lane, Tottenham, N17 8NU

name: Caledonian Park: Clock Tower Tours
description: Opened in 1855 as centrepiece of the Metropolitan Cattle Market. The clock tower offers magnificent views over London. The clock mechanism was made by John Moore of Clerkenwell. The tower has been renovated with help from the Heritage Fund.
address: Cally Clock Tower Centre, Market Road, N7 9HF

name: Caledonian Park: Park Walking Tour
description: Tour of the park and local area, discover how Copenhagen Fields became Caledonian Park and how diplomacy gave way to debauchery and agitation and then butchery and commerce.

name: Canons Park
description: Grade II listed historic park landscape containing several listed buildings, including an 18C 'temple' building, bothy and compound, and walled kitchen garden, converted in 1937 to an informally planted garden by Harrow Council.
address: Donnefield Avenue entrance, Canons Park, Edgware, HA8 6RH

name: Caroline Gardens Chapel
description: An extraordinary centrepiece of a large almshouse complex, the chapel was originally intended for retired publicans and brewers. It was severely damaged in WWII, and is now hired out for exhibitions, events, shoots and wedding ceremonies.

name: Carreducker at 50 Chocolate Studios
description:
A Victorian chocolate factory conversion with exposed girders, brickwork and Crittal-style windows. 

No 50 was transformed from a flat into a traditional, bespoke shoemaking workshop, showroom and shoe & leather craft training school.

name: Carshalton Water Tower and Historic Gardens
description: Early 18C Grade II listed building incorporating plunge bath with Delft tiles, orangery, saloon and pump chamber with part-restored water wheel. Hermitage and sham bridge in grounds.

name: Centre Building: London School of Economics
description: Completed in May 2019, LSE's Centre Building is a state of the art flexible and highly sustainable academic and teaching building, designed by renowned architects Roger Stirk Harbour + Partners.
address: London School of Economics & Political Science, 2 Houghton Street, WC2A 2AD

name: Charlton House
description: London's only surviving great Jacobean mansion, set in Charlton Park, red brick with white stone dressings and classic Jacobean styles. Each room has a unique fireplace coupled with beautiful strap work ceilings and original features.
address: Royal Greenwich Heritage Trust, Charlton House, Charlton Road,, SE7 8RE

name: Chats Palace
description: Homerton Library (Chats Palace) is one of the UK's 660 Carnegie libraries. Designed for “betterment of the people of the East End"  its glass roof, leaded lights, marble floor and pillared frontage testify to the architect's eye for detail.

name: Christ Church
description: Grade II* listed church with ragstone tower, spire, good stained glass by Kempe and recently restored William Hill organ. A characteristic work of Scott. It is Gothic Revival in the style of the 13C.

name: Christ Church Southgate and the Minchenden Oak Garden
description: Grade II listed church with fine collection of Pre-Raphaelite stained glass windows by Morris & Co. including Burne Jones and Rossetti. Wall paintings. Mosaic reredos. Minchenden Oak  - ancient pollarded oak more than 800 years old.

name: Christ Church, Streatham
description: Grade I listed pioneering brick polychromy. Designed with early Christian, Italian, Ottoman, Alhambran, Mamluk, Sevillean and Ancient Egyptian influences with fine mosaics and stained glass by Crane, Bentley. Lee and Hayward.

name: Church of St Lawrence, Little Stanmore
description: Unique Continental Baroque church rebuilt in 1715 by James Brydges, first Duke of Chandos. Painted walls and ceiling with trompe-l'oeil effect. Wood carvings by Grinling Gibbons and the organ on which Handel played.

name: Creative Mile: Brentford Art Trail
description: A celebration of Brentford's creativity, its industrial past, and it's riverside communities, with artist studios and pop-up exhibitions spread across 8 venues along a one-mile walking route running from Kew Bridge down to Johnson's Island.

name: Crime, Punishment & Executions
description: Crime, Punishment & Executions in the City of London

name: Crofton Roman Villa
description: Remains of ten rooms of a masonry Roman villa-house with evidence of opus signinum and tessellated floors. Details of channelled and pillared hypocaust systems. The Villa was the centre of a farming estate of about 500 acres.

name: Crossness Southern Outfall
description: The southern outfall of the Victorian sewerage system designed by Joseph Bazalgette. Grade I and Grade II listed buildings contains four of the largest rotative beam steam engines in the world and amazing Victorian decorative ironwork.
address: The Old Works, Thames Water Sewage Treatment Works, Bazalgette Way, SE2 9AQ

name: Croydon Minster
description: Medieval style church rebuilt by Sir George Gilbert Scott after 1867 fire. Tower & south porch are 15C. Large nave with open timber-work roof leads to chancel dominated by superb stained glass window & rich alabaster reredos.

name: Danson House
description: A stunning Grade I listed Georgian villa designed by the architect of the Bank of England. Set in more than 200 acres of magnificent parkland overlooking Danson Lake.
address: Danson Park, Danson Road, Welling, DA6 8HL

name: Darbishire Place (Peabody Whitechapel Estate)
description: New block of 13 homes which completes an ensemble of six housing blocks surrounding an internal courtyard.The façade complements the existing Victorian buildings by Henry Astley Darbishire. RIBA Award Winner & Stirling Prize shortlist 2015

name: Devonport Mausoleum
description: Beautiful mausoleum in former Royal Navy cemetery, restored 1999 by the University of Greenwich. Many interesting plaques and grave stones.
address: National Maritime Museum, Romney Road, SE10 9NF

name: Dreamings collage art exhibition
description: A collage art exhibition. Every day except Monday and Tuesday. A talk "Why Collage?" on Sunday evening at 7, followed by a Q&A and an art raffle for charity
address: The Brook Pub, 38 New Rd, Brentford TW8 0NU, TW8 0NU

name: Ebury Edge
description: Ebury Edge is a colourful temporary development, providing residents with a continuous community space as the Ebury Bridge Estate is re-developed in phases, together with affordable workspaces and a café.

name: Eco Show Home
description: Waltham Forest Council has transformed a Victorian terrace into an Eco Home to showcase best practice retrofitting to be more carbon friendly. Features home improvements that reduce carbon footprint and help tackle the climate emergency.

name: Enfield Brewery
description: A modern open-plan building that houses fully-functioning and impressive brew house equipment. The exterior looks like a clean modern warehouse style building but the interior is updated with industrial equipment.

name: Enfield To Fork - Edmonton Green Shopping Centre
description: The Museum of Enfield is this year bringing its temporary exhibition to you! “From Enfield to Fork” explores the borough’s history and relationship with food, from Roman Enfield to Market Gardening.

name: Fitzrovia Chapel
description: Loughborough Pearson's red brick building is unimposing from the outside, but inside is a riot of Gothic Revival design. Golden mosaics reveal the character of the Grade II* listed chapel, built as part of the Middlesex Hospital.

name: Former Edmonton Girls' Charity School
description: The former Charity School was constructed in 1793, by Obodiah Legrew, who also purchased the adjoining no.24 Church Street, part of the surviving earlier 18th century range, to create a small cottage for the School Mistress.
address: Charity School Hall (next door to 24 Church Street), N9 9DU

name: Freemasons' Hall
description: Monumental Art Deco exterior belying elaborate and varied interior decoration: extensive use of mosaic, stained glass, decorated ceilings and lighting.
address: Freemasons' Hall, 60 Great Queen Street, WC2B 5AZ

name: Fulham Palace
description: Residence of the Bishop of London until 1973. Tudor red-brick courtyard with Georgian additions & Butterfield Chapel (1867). Walled garden. Completed a National Lottery Heritage Fund restoration project in spring 2019.

name: GARDEN OF EARTHLY DELIGHTS🌱🐝🍅🦋
description: The Garden of Earthly Delights is a community garden and a "meanwhile" space to raise awareness of empty spaces in the city, grow food for the local community and increase biodiversity. We hold workshops and events to which all are welcome.

name: Garden Court Chambers
description: Inigo Jones design 1640 at 59/60 LIF, copied  by 57/58  with portico and elliptical staircase added by Soane.  Refurbished by current occupiers, a barristers' chambers. Retains many original features, staircases, fireplaces and mouldings

name: Garrick's Temple to Shakespeare, Hampton
description: Grade I listed Georgian garden building. Tribute to Shakespeare built in the Ionic style by actor David Garrick. Arcadian Thames-side setting in restored 18C gardens thought to be by Capability Brown.
address: Garrick's Lawn, Hampton Court Road, , Hampton, TW12 2EN

name: German Historical Institute
description: This Grade II* listed building includes an Adam-style ceiling on the 1st floor and a beautiful staircase with wrought-iron balustrade. Once home to the Pharmaceutical Society of Great Britain, it now houses an historical research institute.

name: Greenwich Pumping Station
description: The pumping station was built in 1864 by Sir Joseph Bazalgette chief engineer at the Metropolitan Board of Works. The site has a total of four Grade II listed heritage assets including the pumping stations with East and West Beam Engines.
address: Greenwich Pumping Station, Greenwich High Rd, SE10 8JL

name: Greenwich Yacht Club
description: Contemporary timber and aluminium building using existing pier, offering unique views of the river, the O2 and the Thames Barrier.

name: Guided walk of Ladywell and Brockley Cemeteries including the Non-conformist chapel
description: Starting at the former non-conformist chapel (1858) the walk will take in poets, actors, artists, local dignitaries and war veterans among others.

name: Guildhall Art Gallery
description: Houses the City of London's art collection, built over remains of London's 2C Roman amphitheatre. Façade uses Portland stone and Collyweston stone slates. Interior uses finishes of marble, American elm, damask and painted wall coverings.

name: Hackney Town Hall
description:
Grade II listed Neoclassical building of Art Deco style. 

Link to be provided

name: Hampstead Garden Suburb Free Church
description: Grade I listed Non-conformist church, set in the suburb's integrally planned Central Square to balance St Jude's Church nearby, but with a low concrete dome. Distinctive interior with large Tuscan columns on high brick plinths.
address: Central Square, hampstead Garden Suburb, NW11 7AG

name: Hampstead Parish Church (St John-at-Hampstead)
description: The parish church is a focal point at the end of a row of attractive Georgian terraced houses.  The chapel-like exterior is deceiving and the beautiful interior with its high domed ceilings and beautiful stained glass windows is a surprise.

name: Hanwell Flight of Locks & Three Bridges
description: Flight of locks and side ponds at Hanwell is a Scheduled  Monument. Three Bridges is a unique stacked intersection of road, rail and canal and Brunel's last major railway project. Walks led by knowledgeable enthusiasts.
address: The Fox public house, Green Lane, W7 2PJ

name: Hermitage Community Moorings
description: A development of residential and recreational moorings for historic vessels on the Thames. The unique Pier House, built to a high specification, provides a floating community centre just downstream from Tower Bridge.

name: Historic Deptford – a walk from the Creek to the Thames
description: Starting at the historic crossing point of the river Ravensbourne we will walk north towards the Thames, revealing unique and uncommon vestiges of Deptford’s remarkable history. Organised by the Deptford Society.
address: South exit of Deptford Bridge DLR station at ground level, SE8 4HP

name: Hogarth's House
description: Early 18C red brick home of artist William Hogarth extended significantly c1749-1764. A 2020 extension adds a curved glass wall in the shape of Hogarth's Line of Beauty. Delightful walled garden containing famous ancient mulberry tree.
address: Hogarth Lane, Great West Road, W4 2QN

name: Holborn House
description: A redevelopment of Holborn’s community centre improving and increasing facilities  -  the space has been designed by Stirling prize nominated 6a architects and includes a public artwork for the building, created by artist Cargh Thuring

name: Holy Trinity Church Sloane Square
description: A sumptuous feast of Victorian stained glass and bold sacred sculpture at what Sir John Betjeman called the 'cathedral of the Arts and Crafts movement.' Work by William Morris, Edward Burne-Jones, William Blake and Christopher Whall.
address: 146 Sloane Street (just off Sloane Square), SW1X 9BZ

name: Holy Trinity Church in Bow
description: Holy Trinity Bow, a Grade C listed Church and graveyard built between 1834 and 1841 lies within the Tredegar Square Conservation Area on a site gifted by the developer of Tredegar Square, Sir Charles Morgan.

name: House Mill
description: The World’s largest tidal mill. 5-storey, timber-framed, brick-clad timber watermill with four waterwheels, originally built 1776 to mill grain for distillery trade. Operational until 1940. On historic 3 Mills Site, Clock Mill adjacent.
address: Three Mill Lane, Bromley by Bow , E3 3DU

name: House on the End
description: Replacing unused garages, this end-of-terrace, infill site development is a contemporary reinterpretation of the neighbouring terraces, complementing the streetscape and adding a House on the End.

name: Hoxton Docks
description: Antepavilion Commission offers emerging architects and makers opportunities to create new work through hands-on construction. Works are put on temporary display in Columbia/ Brunswick Wharf, situated on the Regents Canal in Haggerston.

name: Hyde Park Chapel
description: The four-story Church façade and prominent seven-story tower is covered in Portland stone and highlighted by a golden steeple. The interior features the Christus statue and a large mural of the resurrected Jesus Christ.

name: Inner Temple Gardens
description: Established by the Knights Templar in 1195, The Inner Temple has had a Gardener since 1307. Surviving The Great Fire of London, and the Blitz, the Gardens remain a secret tranquil oasis in heart of the city.
address: The Inner Temple Gardens, Crown Office Row, EC4Y 7BS

name: Isokon Building (Lawn Road Flats)
description: Grade I listed 1934 residential block of flats in Hampstead, designed by the Canadian modernist architect Wells Coates for clients Jack and Molly Pritchard. English Heritage blue plaque for Bauhaus masters Gropius, Breuer and Moholy-Nagy.

name: Jubilee Market
description: The Jubilee Hall, which houses the Jubilee Market, was built in 1904 in the heart of Covent Garden and gained Grade 2 listed status in 1980. The market was officially re opened after renovation by Queen Elizabeth II in 1987.
address: 1  Tavistock Place, The Piazza, Covent Garden, WC2E 8BD, WC2E 8BD

name: Kaymet Factory
description: The operational factory of Kaymet, a maker of trays and trolleys since 1947. A hidden 1950s building with a small yard, originally a printing works. It is brick built, with clear-storey glazing and tubular truss north-light main shed roof.

name: Keats House
description: Keats House is the beautiful Regency villa, where Romantic poet John Keats found inspiration, friendship and love. Today, it is a museum provided by the City of London Corporation for the benefit of London and the nation.

name: Kempton Steam Museum
description: 1920s water pumping station comprising of several architectural styles. Interior retains original steam pumping machinery and historic electrical equipment.
address: Kempton Park Pumping Station, Snakey Lane, TW13 7ND

name: Kenwood
description: A striking Neoclassical villa in tranquil gardens on Hampstead Heath, Kenwood boasts breath-taking interiors by Robert Adam and a world-class art collection. For guaranteed entry, book your free ticket via the English Heritage website.

name: Kilmorey Mausoleum
description: Egyptian-style, pink and grey mausoleum created for the second Earl of Kilmorey. The form relates to the shrines at the heart of Egyptian Temples.
address: 275 St Margaret's Road (opposite Ailsa Tavern), TW1 1NJ

name: King George V Pumping Station
description: Designed to pump water from the River Lee into the King George V reservoir, the building houses three old disused gas Humphrey pumps, and two electric pumps currently in service.

name: King's Cross Public Realm
description: King's Cross is a 67 acre development in Central London being transformed into a new city quarter with 20 regenerated heritage buildings, new homes, offices, public spaces, shops, galleries, bars, restaurants, schools and a university.
address: Western Transit Shed, 11 Stable Street, N1C 4AB

name: Kingsbury and Colindale: Re-imagining Suburbia
description: What does suburbia mean in 2021? As we negotiate how and where we live in a post-pandemic world, the redevelopment of Colindale and Kingsbury reflects wider trends within Greater London but with a unique twist

name: Kingston Edible Forest 2100
description: A mixed orchard of mostly perennial fruit and vegetables in a natural style to create a woodland and a delightful oasis.
address: Southern end of Knollmead Allotments, Knollmead, Tolworth, KT5 9QP

name: Kingston Historic walk
description:
We are  running our usual guided walking tours around historic Kingston this year with reduced numbers. The tour will be the same but fewer numbers will make it safer for all.
Our guided tours are informative, interesting and fun.
address: Market house, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 1JX

name: Kirkaldy's Testing Works
description: Proudly carved over the door are the words ‘Facts not Opinions’. Inside, the authentic sight - and smell - of Kirkaldy’s Testing and Experimenting Works is a unique and direct link with an ingenious age of engineering.

name: Lambeth Town Hall
description: Landmark Edwardian Baroque style town hall with 1930s assembly room.  All in red brick and Portland stone . New atrium, reception and courtyard space along with historic marble staircase and ornate council chamber. Grade II listed.

name: Lansbury Lawrence Primary School
description: Lansbury Lawrence (formally Susan Lawrence and Elizabeth Lansbury) opened in the 1951 Festival of Britain as a showpiece of the Live Architecture exhibition in the Lansbury Estate. An interesting mid-century design with original features.

name: Lanterna, Fish Island Village
description: Designed by Lyndon Goode Architects, Lanterna acts as a gateway to our Fish Island Village development with Hill and was shortlisted for a prestigious Royal Institute of British Architects (RIBA) London Award for architectural excellence.
address: Lanterna Building, Fish Island Village, E3 2LX

name: Lauderdale House
description: Grade II* listed building in Waterlow Park dating to 1582 and recently refurbished. Original Tudor wooden framework adapted by successive owners over the centuries. Today the house runs primarily as an arts, heritage and education centre.

name: Lexi Cinema
description: A contemporary extension to the Lexi Cinema. The building is a composition of brick and stainless steel; a nod to the parapets of surrounding terraces that reflect the changing clouds above, blending with the sky.

name: Little Angel Theatre
description: Little Angel Theatre was converted from a derelict temperance hall in 1961 and has been showcasing puppetry performances ever since. It is London's only purpose-built puppet theatre, due to the existence of its marionette bridge.

name: London Museum of Water & Steam
description: The Museum is housed within in a unique collection of Grade I and II listed buildings. Even though they were purpose-built and purely functional buildings, the architect took great care to make the buildings aesthetically pleasing.

name: Manor House Gardens Ice House
description: Grade II listed ice well and underground chambers (1770) in Manor House Gardens park, which provided ice for nearby Manor House. Cited in 2002 Civic Trust Awards.

name: Markfield Beam Engine and House
description:
A masterpiece of Victorian engineering, Markfield Beam Engine provided a vital public health facility from 1855-1964. 

Steaming demonstrations, 4 & 5 Sept from 12.30pm.

Set in Markfield Park along side the River Lee.
address: Markfield Park, Markfield Road, South Tottenham, N15 4RB

name: Maryland House
description: Maryland House sits on an 8.5 x 9m plot. Over 3 floors, the development holds a basement w/ 3.1m ceilings, 2 bd, 3 ba, studio space, and amenity on each level. Connected by a deep red staircase, light is spread via a glass blocks enclosure.

name: Millennium Mills
description: Built in the early 20C by flour company Spillers, the Art Deco landmark has stood vacant since the decline of the docks as a working port in the 1980s.
address: North Woolwich Road, Royal Docks, E16 1UR

name: Moravian Close
description: A former stable yard of Sir Thomas More's Chelsea estate, now an 18C Chapel, other buildings, and burial ground. Parts of the enclosing walls are Tudor in origin. Ernest and Mary Gillick enhanced the grounds in the 20C.

name: Museum of London
description: Part of an ambitious redevelopment of the area following WWll bombing, this building forms part of the Barbican complex. The architects were inspired by post-war modernism to include green design elements and raised walkways.

name: Museum of Neoliberalism
description: The museum is situated in a shopfront in Leegate Shopping Centre, which has been described by the Evening Standard as "the worst shopping precinct in the country."

name: New Ground (online only)
description: 25 homes designed with the Older Women’s Co-Housing group using PTE’s ‘fabric first’ approach which maximises the benefits of orientation, air-tightness and insulation and following the co-housing model.
address: 5b Union Street, Chipping Barnet, Barnet, London, EN5 4DF

name: New Museum of London, West Smithfield
description: The Museum of London is creating a new museum in the derelict General Market and adjacent post-war Poultry Market. For the first time in 20 years we are inviting the public to explore these spaces in historic and creative Smithfield.

name: New Scotland Yard
description: The Met Police’s home on the Embankment, created from the 1930s Curtis Green building with a new curved glass pavilion entrance and extensions to the rooftop and rear. Winner of the 2017 Prime Minister’s Better Public Building Award.

name: New West End Synagogue
description: Grade I listed Victorian synagogue, Audsley's masterpiece.  Includes metalwork, stained glass and a mosaic; stained glass by NHJ Westlake. Further enrichment 1894-5 included lighting designed by George Aitchison.

name: New zawiya in Bethnal Green
description: The School of Sufi Teaching's new zawiya has input from an international group of architects, artists and craftspersons who have woven Islamic design principles into the context of the Globe Town Conservation Area.

name: Nunhead Cemetery
description: Magnificent Victorian cemetery with Gothic chapel & restored & ruined lodge. One of London's wildest cemeteries. Part restored with the help of a lottery grant. 52 acres of woodland, with bats, owls, foxes & squirrels. Grade II* landscape.

name: Oak Room, New River Head
description: Formerly boardroom of the 17C water house, the Oak Room is a fine late Renaissance room demonstrating the New River Company's wealth. 1697 carved oak interior, attributed to Grinling Gibbons, including overmantel and panels over the doors.
address: New River Head, , 173 Rosebery Avenue, EC1R 4UL

name: Old Operating Theatre Museum & Herb Garret
description: St Thomas' Church attic (1703) once part of old St Thomas' Hospital, houses the hospital's Herb Garret and the oldest surviving operating theatre (1822) in Europe.

name: Old Royal Naval College - Admiral's House, Jacobean Undercroft, talks in the grounds and Smartphone tour
description: Sir Christopher Wren's riverside masterpiece in Greenwich, built as the Royal Hospital for Seamen and begun in 1696.
address: Old Royal Naval College, Greenwich, SE10 9NN

name: Old Royal Naval College - King William Court
description: Wren-designed building completed under the direction of Hawksmoor and Vanbrugh, 1698-1712. Original wood panelling, refurbished by Dannatt Johnson in 2001 for University of Greenwich.
address: King William Court, 30 Park Row, SE10 9NN

name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Mary Court
description: Last major building on the site (1751). Original layout, timber panelling, barrel vaulting and Portland stone. Refurbished in 2000 by Dannatt Johnson for University of Greenwich.
address: Queen Mary Court, 30 Park Row, SE10 9NN

name: Order and Disorder: Guildhall to Smithfield
description: Head for the dark side of the City and discover tales of crime and punishment, heroes and villains, the great monastic houses, notorious Newgate Prison, body snatchers, Smithfield Market, Bartholomew Fair and the road to the gallows.
address: Gresham Street, City of London, EC2V

name: Painters' Hall
description: Acquired in 1532 and rebuilt in 1670 after the Great Fire, the Hall was partially destroyed in 1941 by enemy action and rebuilt in a Neo-Georgian style in 1960. The original charter, portraiture and stained glass are of particular interest.

name: Paxton Locher House
description: A unique modern courtyard house making brilliant use of a restricted site. A retractable glass roof gives wonderful natural light and opens the house to the sky in dry weather.

name: Peter Jones
description: Grade II* listed building, involving complex mix of new build and restoration. Britain's first ever curtain walling and listed features such as spiral staircase. Sloane Room has one of best views over Chelsea. RIBA Award Winner 2005.

name: Phoenix Gardens Community Building
description: The first purpose-built new-build community centre to be built in the heart of Soho for generations, located within the renowned Phoenix Gardens.

name: Pitzhanger Manor & Gallery
description: Designed by Sir John Soane as a family home and country residence. Following a three-year conservation project,  Pitzhanger has been returned to Soane’s innovative original design and re-opened to the public in March 2019.

name: Polish Social and Cultural Association
description: Built 1971-74 in brutalist style. The largest Polish centre in Western Europe, it contains a theatre, the Polish Library, the Polish University Abroad, a Joseph Conrad collection, Jazz Café, art gallery and art collection on public display.

name: Processes of Attunement: A Walk Along London's Riverbank
description: Theatrum Mundi will be hosting a walk of the London riverbank guided by curator Andrea Cetrulo, artist Chiara Ambrosio and writer Labeja Kodua Okullu based on Interior Realms, a book recently by Theatrum Mundi Editions.

name: Pullman Court
description: Grade II* listed buildings, modern movement style with balcony walkways and period internal features.

name: RC Church of St Mellitus (St Mellitus Organ Restoration Project)
description: A grandiose neo-classical building with impressive interior built in 1870-1, formerly New Court Congregational church and home to the Hunter pipe organ, built in memory of local WW1 soldiers and recently restored with Lottery funding.
address: Church of St Mellitus, Tollington Park, N4 3AG

name: ROOM by Antony Gormley
description: A monumental, inhabitable sculpture placed on a wing of the listed façade of The Beaumont Hotel. The interior, a bedroom, is as important as its exterior: a giant crouching cuboid figure based on the artist's body.
address: The Beaumont, Brown Hart Gardens, 8 Balderton Street, W1K 6TF

name: Reform Club
description: Built as a Whig gentleman's club and inspired by Italian Renaissance palaces. Lobby leads to an enclosed colonnaded courtyard with complementary glazed roof and tessellated floor. Tunnelled staircase leads to upper floor.

name: Ripple Greenway and the Lost Words Art Trail
description:
Ripple Greenway is a beautiful 14-acre linear park and art trail.  Home to Katy Hallett’s steel sculptures, inspired by Robert Macfarlane’s and Jackie Morris’ The Lost Words.
Wooden play and exercise equipment, picnic tables and benches.

name: Roca London Gallery
description: A unique space where water acts as the architectural theme - offering an innovative and interactive experience with Roca, the global bathroom brand.

name: Roe Green Village
description: Built in 1918-19 to provide housing for AirCo (the Aircraft Manufacturing Company based in Colindale), Roe Green was designed in the garden village idiom by Sir Frank Baines, HM Office of Works principal architect.

name: Round Chapel
description: Grade II* listed Nonconformist chapel for 1,000 people. Described by Pevsner as 'one of the finest Nonconformist buildings in London'. Horseshoe plan, innovative cast-iron columns and tracery, restored as a centre for the performing arts.
address: Lower Clapton Road (junction with Glenarm Road), E5 0NP

name: Royal College of Physicians
description: One of London's most important and provocative post-war Grade I listed buildings set amongst the Regency terraces of Regent’s Park. It’s white mosaic exterior with distinct modernist lines draws visitors in to dramatic interior spaces.
address: 11 St Andrew's Place, Regents Park, NW1 4LE

name: Royal Hospital Chelsea, home of the Chelsea Pensioners
description: Numbered amongst the UK's architectural glories and boasting 66 acres of beautiful grounds, the Royal Hospital Chelsea has been home to the iconic Army veteran community fondly known as the 'Chelsea Pensioners' since its foundation in 1692.

name: Royal Opera House
description: Housing the Royal Opera and the Royal Ballet, the historic building was reconfigured in 2018 by Stanton Williams to deliver not only world-class performance spaces, but also a welcoming and inclusive cultural and social hub.

name: Royal Over-Seas League
description: Over-Seas House is an amalgamation of two Grade I listed buildings – Rutland House (James Gibbs, 1736) and Vernon House (1835 rebuilt 1905), with an Art Deco style wing added in 1937.
address: Park Place, St James's Street, SW1A 1LR

name: Rudolf Steiner House
description: Unique example of Expressionist architecture in London with sculptural staircase based on organic plant forms. Grade II listed. New cafe area and renovations in 2008. Refurbishment of theatre and foyer 2020.

name: Self-guided Old Malden Walk
description: The walk is around Old Malden and covers residential developments within the district. Different styles of suburban architecture includes a selection of modernist housing. There are also historic buildings and other places of interest.
address: Manor Drive North, Greater London, KT3 5PN

name: Self-guided Tower Gardens Garden Suburb Walk
description: One of the first garden suburbs in the world, 2-storey terraced cottages retaining decorative architectural features. LCC created 'housing of the working classes' role for architects' department under Riley, member of the Art Workers guild.
address: 5 Tower Gardens Road, Tower Gardens , N17 7PX

name: Senate House
description: London’s tallest secular building when it opened as the HQ of the University of London and home to the Ministry of Information during WWII, this Grade II* listed landmark features Classicism and Art Deco elements.
address: University of London, Malet Street, WC1E 7HU

name: Severndroog Castle
description: Grade II* listed triangular brick Georgian tower sited in Oxleas Woods. Standing 63ft tall, it offers spectacular panoramic views across the capital. It was built in 1784 by Lady Anne James in memory of her husband Sir William James.
address: Castle Wood, Shooters Hill, Greenwich, SE18 3RT

name: Sex, Death and Shopping
description: Join @Meetmrlondoner for ‘Sex, Death and Shopping’. This walking tour explores the seamier side of Soho’s chaotic past and present. Discover streets with dark secrets; stumble upon a plague pit and touch the cloth of London's best tailors.
address: Liberty of London  - west door, Great Marlborough Street/ Kingly St junction, W1B 5AH

name: Shepherds Bush Baptist Tabernacle WW1 Hall
description: The Tabernacle Memorial Hall is nestled behind the Tabernacle Church on Shepherds Bush road just off the green. Used as an office space for many years, it has been refurbished and restored into a complimentary health and wellbeing centre.
address: The Tabernacle Memorial Hall, Miller's Way, W6 7NH

name: Sir Richard Burton's Mausoleum
description: Grade II* listed mausoleum in the form of an Arab tent with ripples in the stone imitating canvas. Interior is embellished with oriental lamps, devotional paintings and camel bells.
address: St Mary Magdalen's RC Church, 61 North Worple Way, Mortlake, SW14 8PR

name: Slavery and the City
description: We will explore sites and institutions with direct links to the history of slavery and hear why the apologies were made last year, whilst wandering within the story packed streets and alleyways of the Square Mile.

name: South London Gallery
description: Public contemporary art gallery housed in 3 listed Victorian buildings restored by 6a architects. Comprising galleries, café, shop, gardens, kitchen and converted Victorian Fire Station.

name: Southwark Pupil Referral Unit
description: The Southwark Pupil Referral Unit is a new school for 11-14 year olds who have been excluded from mainstream schools or are at risk of exclusion. The aim is to reintegrate these students into mainstream education.

name: St Alban Church
description: Notable 1930s Grade II listed church with Swedish and German influences externally. Landmark tower. Stepped tunnel-vault with arches to side aisle walls giving a light lively interior. Marquetry panelling to Lady Chapel.

name: St Alfege Church, Greenwich
description: Magnificent English Baroque church, Grade I listed, gutted by fire in 1941 and restored by Sir Albert Richardson to original design. Many original features. Burial site of Thomas Tallis, organist/choirmaster (1505-85).

name: St Andrew's Kingsbury (new church)
description: Meticulous 1930s rebuilding (complete with original furnishings) of an 1840s Marylebone church. Grade I listed. Contains works by Pugin, Burges, Street, Pearson and Butterfield.
address: junction of Church Lane/Tudor Gardens/ Old Church Lane, Kingsbury, NW9 8RZ

name: St Anne's Church, Limehouse
description: St Anne's Limehouse has been described as 'the finest parish church in England.' Designed by Nicholas Hawksmoor, it is Grade I listed and one of the Major Churches in the Church of England. It is home to a thriving Christian congregation.

name: St Barnabas Church
description: Early English style, full of Pre-Raphaelite decoration. Important works by Bodley, Comper and Cundy and windows by Kempe and Tower. First Oxford Movement church. Recently restored 10 bell peal; bell ringing quarter peal once a month

name: St Barnabas' Church and Mission Hall
description: Early 20th C Grade II* listed church designed by CH Reilly. Byzantine in structure but prefiguring Modernism in its aesthetic, Nairn judged it “the best church of its date in London”, Reilly “the building I should like to be remembered by”.
address: St Barnabas' Church, Shackewell Row, E8 2EA

name: St Benet Fink Church
description: J S Alder's most complete and unaltered church, at the church's consecration in 1912 it was referred to as 'the little Cathedral' thanks to its light and airy Gothic design.

name: St Bride Foundation
description: Built in 1893 as a printers' institute in the Anglo-Dutch style, with sandstone dressings, steeply pitched tiled roof and gables; many original features remain including the swimming pool and library.

name: St Bride's Church, Fleet Street
description: Wren designed building of 1675, interior lost in blitz of 1940, reopened 1957 with 'Wren inspired' interior
address: St Bride's Church, St Bride's Avenue, EC4Y 8AU

name: St Dunstan and All Saints Church
description: Grade I listed early medieval parish church (from 952 before Tower of London) in spacious churchyard. Fine interior: Anglo-Saxon Rood, Norman font, 'squint', fine memorials incl founders of Trinity House, 1950s glass. Bells of Stepney.

name: St John the Baptist Holland Road
description: Possibly the last stone-vaulted building built in London – of soaring nobility embellished with carvings and fittings of exceptional quality.

name: St Jude on the Hill
description: Eccentric Edwardian church, Grade I listed. Described by Simon Jenkins as 'one of Lutyens' most distinctive creations'. Extensive 20C wall-paintings by Walter Starmer, memorial to horses of WWI. Local archives display.

name: St Leonards Court Air Raid Shelter, East Sheen
description: The Air Raid Shelter was first built in 1939 for the the residents of St Leonards Court. A dormitory annex with 48 beds was added in 1940.  Some of the original features, such as handmade lampshades, are remarkably well preserved.

name: St Martin's Parish Church, West Drayton
description:
A Grade II* listed church dating from 13th century with some interesting features
Adjacent to a 16th century Gate House

name: St Mary The Virgin Wanstead
description: One of the finest examples of Georgian architecture. It has been hardly altered since built. The church is a rectangular building of Portland stone, with a projecting chancel. Two external walls were restored in 2019. Grade I listed
address: St Mary The Virgin Church , Overton Drive, E11 2LW

name: St Mary the Virgin
description: Small Grade I listed 12C chapel in lovely churchyard setting, it retains original architectural features and has interesting brasses, monuments and stained glass windows.
address: Church Road, Manor Park, Little Ilford, E12 6HA

name: St Mary's Church, Battersea
description: Classic Grade I listed Georgian church with outstanding interior and monuments. Renovated 2019/20.

name: St Michael and All Angels Church
description: James Maltby Bignall (1827-1885) worked in the practice of Sir George Gilbert Scott, the architect of St Pancras Station. The style of St Michael's is late Gothic Revival, in its size and height reminiscent of Northern European churches.

name: St Pancras Chambers and Clock Tower
description: Former Midland Grand Hotel, now St Pancras Renaissance Hotel and Chambers apartments. Includes hotel lobby and clock tower.
address: The Forecourt, St Pancras Station, Euston Road, NW1 2AR

name: St Pancras Church & Crypt
description: Unique Greek-style parish church. Grade I listed building inspired by the ionic temple of the Erechtheum on the Acropolis. A notable feature are the Caryatids guarding the entrances to the crypt.
address: Euston Road/Upper Woburn Place NW1, NW1 2BA

name: St Paul's Bow Common
description: Described as 'the most significant church built after the WWII in Britain' - Brutalist, inclusive and influential signpost for future church design.
address: Corner of Burdett Road/ St Paul's Way, E3 4AR

name: St Paul's, Newington
description: Modern architecture church with large copper and lead roof and concrete, brick and stained glass external structure. Marble, wood and plaster interior and artwork by Sculptor Freda Pinto and Gerald Holtom.

name: St Peter & St Paul Harlington
description: Grade I listed church dating from 1086, with Norman font and Norman stone arch, carved with cats heads. Interesting monuments including Easter sepulchre, ancient yew tree in churchyard. Good restoration between 1830 and 1860.
address: St Peter's Way, High Street, Harlington, UB3 5AB

name: St Peter-in-the-Forest Church & Community Centre
description: An 'Italian Romanesque' church set in Epping Forest, St Peter's was founded in 1840 and extended in 1887. The building underwent a major reordering throughout 2020 to save it from subsidence and create new community facilities.

name: St Vedast alias Foster
description: 12C church. During the Great Fire of 1666 the church building escaped total destruction, and was restored. Christopher Wren was eventually called in to rebuild St Vedast, completing the work in October 1673.

name: St. Mary's Church, Walthamstow Village
description: Churchyard of the ancient Parish Church of St Mary, Walthamstow; an area of three & one third acres containing over 1300 monuments including four Grade II listed tombs. Burial records date from 1743.
address: Church End (top of Church Hill), Walthamstow, E17 9RL

name: Stanley Halls
description: A public hall, theatre and gallery in grand Edwardian style. Grade II listed, Stanley made fun of the Victorian style with grand ornamentation. It reflects Stanley's interest in science, the arts and public cultural improvement.

name: Sukkat Shalom Reform Synagogue
description: Grade II* listed, originally the Merchant Seaman's Orphan Asylum, bought by the synagogue in 1995 and restored with Lottery Fund grant. Timber work and windows from a synagogue which was inside the Tottenham Home for Incurables.

name: Sutton Estate
description: The Sutton Estate has been providing low cost, social housing for over a century, and it does so right in the heart of some of the most expensive real estate in Europe.

name: The Antique Breadboard Museum, Putney
description: Located in a Conservation Zone designated in 1970, the building is one of a charming labyrinth of early Victorian cottages which grew up around Quill Lane,  the oldest cut-through from the Thames to the Upper Richmond Road.

name: The Art Workers' Guild
description: 1713 terraced house with 1914 hall at rear. Notable renovated Arts and Crafts interior. Newly refurbished glass vaulted courtyard. Portraits of Guild Masters since 1884.

name: The Brentford Gallery
description: Johnson's Island is an artist's community, set on an island on the Grand Union Canal in West London. It is home to a thriving creative community.
address: Johnsons Island, Catherine Wheel Road, Brentford, TW8 8BD

name: The British Academy
description: One of London's finest examples of Georgian architecture, Carlton House Terrace was designed by John Nash and built between 1827 and 1833. It is home to the British Academy, the UK’s national academy for the humanities and social sciences.

name: The Camera Club
description: Victorian building renovated in 1990 into a photographic gallery, studio and darkrooms to house one of the world's oldest photographic societies.

name: The Cartoon Museum
description: Underground museum. Interior design by Sam Jacobs Studio. Design concept influenced by cartoon and comic narrative techniques.
address: The Cartoon Museum, 63 Wells St, W1A 3AE

name: The Changing Face of Brentford
description: The walk starts in the Medieval market place, proceeds  through 17C development and 18C housing then explores 19/20C industrial legacy and striking new 21C Thames-side regeneration schemes.

name: The Chapter House, Merton Priory
description: Fascinating excavated foundations of the Chapter House of Merton Priory c1100-1200, one of the most important of all Augustinian monasteries prior to its destruction in 1538 by Henry VIII. The remains lie under Merantun Way (A24).
address: Merton Abbey Mills, Merantun Way, SW19 2RD

name: The Church of Our Most Holy Redeemer
description: A unique II* listed Italianate church by John Dando Sedding with attached Campanile and Institute Building. Of particular significance in the church is the imposing baldacchino over the High Altar, which dominates the east end.

name: The City Churches: St Mary-le-Bow
description: Founded by William the Conqueror's Archbishop Lanfranc in 1080 (the significant crypt survives) St Mary-le-Bow was rebuilt, notably by Wren after the Great Fire and by Laurence King in 1964 after WWII destruction. Home of Bow Bells.

name: The City Churches: St Stephen Walbrook
description: Wren's own and 'finest City Church'.  Fantastic architecture with different shapes,  twelve Corinthian columns and covered by huge dome - first of its type. Central stone altar by Henry Moore installed in 1987. Birthplace of the Samaritans.

name: The Conservatoire, Blackheath
description: Part of the oldest surviving purpose-built cultural complex in London, founded by the community through the purchase of bonds in 1881. Arguably the finest in London, the main art studio is spacious with a magnificent north light.

name: The Great Barn, Harmondsworth
description: The timbers of this great medieval barn (1426-7), over 190 feet long and nearly 40 feet high, are 95% original. Displays include the conservation/repairs carried out in 2014 and its place in the agricultural history of the village.
address: Manor Court, High Street, Harmondsworth, UB7 0AQ

name: The Great Fire of London
description: The Great Fire of London

name: The Hospital Chapel of St Mary & St Thomas
description: Founded c1145 by the Abbess of Barking as a hospice for thirteen old and infirm men, the present building is 12C and 19C. Grade II* listed with many interesting monuments, including Burne-Jones windows.

name: The Library at Willesden Green
description: A modern 4-storey building incorporating the much-loved Victorian library. The galleries and feature walls display exhibitions and contemporary art and a dramatic central atrium provides natural ventilation and daylight throughout.

name: The Mildmay Club
description: A rare example of a large purpose built metropolitan working men’s club with over 100 years of history. A once dignified building, revival Queen Anne style in the late-Victorian period, Grade II listed in 2019.

name: The Musical Museum
description: The current building was specially designed for the Musical Museum, and was opened in June 2008.  In addition to the instrument galleries and roll library, the Museum contains a workshop, concert hall, and a café with views of the river.

name: The North Wing, St Bartholomew's 'Barts' Hospital
description: Founded in 1123 and rebuilt to designs of James Gibbs. Barts' Grade I listed North Wing showcases spectacular canvases by William Hogarth & the historic Great Hall. Museum & touring exhibition from the Wellcome Collection also open.
address: St Bartholomew's Hospital, West Smithfield, EC1A 7BE

name: The Old Deanery
description: This Grade I Mansion House, close to St Paul's Cathedral was probably designed by Edward Woodroofe in 1669 and completed in 1673.  The residence of successive Deans of St Pauls until the 1970's today it is the office to the Bishop of London
address: The Old Deanery, Deans Court, EC4V 5AA

name: The Old Finsbury Town Hall
description: Opened by Lord Rosebery, an ornate building with elegant decor influenced by the Art Nouveau movement. Several notable rooms including the Great Hall with unique stained glass, antique mirrors and Clerkenwell Angel statuettes.

name: The Old Library - Acton High Street
description: The red-brick property has an ornate façade facing Acton High Street.  It consists of two storeys with part third storey and is one of the historic civic buildings known as the Redbrick Quarter because of their distinctive appearance.

name: The Old Stables
description: Originally built as horses stables next to the Grand union Canal for a local brewery, it has been used to store barrage balloons and  various industrial uses over the years, currently used as an artist studio.
address: The Old Stables, Catherine Wheel Road, BRENTFORD, TW8 8BD

name: The Royal Bell
description: The Royal Bell is a Grade II listed hotel that has lain empty for over ten years. Designed by Ernest Newton in 1898, it was one of three coaching inns in Bromley and an important centre of Victorian and Edwardian culture.

name: The Royal Society
description: A spectacular Grade I listed building designed by famed architect John Nash. Built in 1831, these former townhouses have undergone refurbishments throughout their history. The building is now home to the UK's national science academy.
address: The Royal Society, 6-9 Carlton House Terrace, SW1Y 5AG

name: The Sponge
description: An imaginative solution to today's contrasting needs of open spaces and privacy. A large open plan ground floor is carved by joinery items and a wooden slatted box leading to the basement. Natural light filters through the whole house.

name: The Stanley Picker Trust, Picker House (online only)
description: Completed in 1968 by Kenneth Wood, RIBA, T Eng (CEI).  A time capsule of the 1960s, it is set in a quiet cul-de-sac on steeply sloping ground which both inspired and challenged the architect when creating the modern split-level design.

name: The Steamship Project Space
description: With a sculpture garden, performance art in the attic and live music in the bowels of The Steamship, built in the heart of Docklands 1885, the resident artists show how the area has transformed and how they've transformed the former pub.
address: The Steamship Project Space, 24 Naval Row, E14 9PS

name: The Temple Church
description: Medieval architecture meets Wren's refurbishments in this inspiring building, the Mother Church of the Common Law. The Magna Carta exhibit: has William Marshal and King John where they would have debated and agreed clauses of Magna Carta.

name: The Temple Wanstead Park
description: The Temple, 1760 remnant of magnificent Wanstead House estate, set in Grade II listed landscape Wanstead Park. Displays within, activities for all under Doric portico & in grassed enclosure.

name: The Textile Building
description: Original 2-story garment factory built in 1933. Additional stories were added and taken over by Burberry in the '50s, becoming global HQ until 2006. A two-phase residential redevelopment added another 2 stories, with ground floor studios.
address: Studio 1, Textile Building, 29a Chatham Place, E9 6NY

name: The Victorian Society
description: Part of the original Bedford Park development restored by the Victorian Society and used as their headquarters since the 1970s. Picturesque style;  3-storeys,  Red and yellow brick; Dutch gable; oriel windows.  Dated 1880.

name: The Wheelhouse
description: Listed building with unique 7-spoke Victorian waterwheel, the only daily working example in South London, originally used by Liberty's for rinsing printed silk, and now the home of a craft pottery and art studio.
address: Merton Abbey Mills, Merantun Way, SW19 2RD

name: Tooting Bec Lido
description: Outdoor pool 100x33 yards. One million gallons of unheated water. Iconic outdoor cubicle doors, fountain and café added in the 1930s, with Art Deco style entrance in 2001. Sports hall pavilion added in 2016.
address: Tooting Bec Lido, Tooting Bec Road, SW16 1RU

name: Tottenham Green Conservation Area
description: External tour of buildings including 18C Georgian houses, 19C Jewish Hospital, Prince of Wales Hospital and Holy Trinity Church, ancient High Cross Monument, Edwardian Town Hall complex, housing developments and Bernie Grant Arts Centre.
address: Town Hall Approach Road, , N15 4RY, N15 4RY

name: Tower Theatre
description: Built as a chapel in 1875, this octagonal brick building has also served as a synagogue, an office and a gym. Now this local landmark has been brought back into use as a theatre for the Tower Theatre Company.

name: Town of tomorrow: Thamesmead Through Film
description: Touted as a ‘town of tomorrow’, Thamesmead’s ambitious masterplan captured global attention when it was first built in the 1960s. This new town offered a leap forward into what was seen as futuristic living for visitors and residents.

name: Trevithick House
description: Pre war social housing flats, red brick, Georgian sash windows, playground, allotments and washing lines outside.

name: Trinity Buoy Wharf/Container City
description: Home to London's only lighthouse, fine stock buildings and examples of the innovative Container City buildings. This former buoy manufacturing site is now a centre for the creative industries with various sculptures and installations.

name: Turning Earth Ceramics E10
description: Ceramics centre for the Lee Valley, covering the entire top floor of an old hardware factory. Three rooms, providing just over 8000 sq ft of floor space; the main room is capped by its original saw-tooth glass roof feature.

name: Two Temple Place
description: By gothic revivalist architect, John Loughborough Pearson, and completed in 1895 for William Waldorf Astor as his estate office, the building overlooks the River Thames and embodies the outstanding workmanship of the late Victorian period.

name: Twofold House
description: Large, openable glass-to-glass sliding doors sit seemingly precariously underneath a massive cantilever and a facetted roof rises up to meet a skylight at the highest point of this imposing extension in the Woodgrange Conservation Area.

name: UCL Pearl
description: UCL PEARL is a brand new building designed to be a laboratory that can "house the world" so that we can create different environments from around the world for experiments about people and the environment around them.
address: UCL PEARL, Yew Tree Avenue, RM10 7FN

name: University of Chicago Booth School of Business
description: Chicago Booth's London campus combines the best of old and new. Located near St. Paul's, the campus features more than 50 pieces of contemporary art and houses our Executive MBA Programme Europe, Executive Education, and conference centre.
address: One Bartholomew Close, Barts Square, EC1A 7BL

name: University of Greenwich, Stockwell Street
description: The building features a limestone exterior designed to 'complement but not mimic' the surrounding historical architecture, whilst behind the façade is a 4-storey composition of steel, glass and exposed concrete.

name: Uxbridge Quaker Meeting House
description: An early 19C meeting house, with a little-altered large meeting room, within a garden – retains much of its original character and fabric, full-height shutters and fixed seating in the elders’ stand. Site of Quaker worship from late 1600s.
address: 150 York Road (corner of Belmont Road) , Uxbridge, UB8 1QW

name: Valentines Mansion & Gardens
description: Large, late 17C Grade II* listed house with fine staircase and Venetian window and Georgian additions, used as a family dwelling until the early 1900s. Reopened to the public in Feb 2009 following extensive restoration works.

name: Van Gogh House London
description: The carefully renovated Van Gogh House seeks to share its story and inspire a new generation of artists through Van Gogh’s London story. The house curates a dynamic programme of events anchored in the artist’s practice and local heritage.

name: Walk in Brookmill Park
description: Explore this little known park encompassing riverbanks along the tidal Ravensbourne, an old railway embankment, magnificent plane, lime and beech trees, pond, formal area, view of architect David Adjaye's Stephen Lawrence Centre.

name: Walter Segal Self-build Houses
description: A close of 13 self-built houses. Each is unique, built using method developed by Walter Segal, who led the project in the 1980s. Houses have been extended and renovated. Sustainable features including solar electric, water & space heating.
address: Walters Way, Honor Oak Park , SE23 3LH

name: Walthamstow Pumphouse Museum
description: Grade II listed Victorian engine house remodelled to take a pair of 1895 Marshall steam engines, still in working order. A museum celebrating the rich Boroughs and the Lea Valley Region Industrial Heritage.

name: Wellbeing Walk: South Kensington
description: Our walking tour takes inspiration from the streets of South Kensington to explore practical ways to support wellbeing and find pools of calm in the midst of London's buzz and bustle.

name: West India Dock Impounding Station
description: The recently automated impounding station controls the water level in the docks using the original Worthington Simpson pumps driven by Lancashire dynamo.
address: Western end of Marsh Wall, E14 8JT

name: Westbourne Park Baptist Church
description: The building is a church worship area with an additional hall, meeting rooms, offices, a children's library and 33 affordable units of accommodation made up of one, two and three bedroom flats.
address: Corner of Porchester Road and Westbourne Park Villas, W2 5DX

name: Westminster to Waterloo Reach: Festival of Britain 70 years on
description: The tour will consider the shifting political plans for the festival that began in the mid 1930s and celebrate the planners, designers and architects employed by the then London County Council behind its success.
address: County Hall, The Queen's Walk, SE1 7PB

name: Wharf Road
description: Designed by architects Pollard Thomas Edwards, the £50m scheme delivered 98 new homes. 80 per cent of the homes are affordable including 64 for social rent. Wharf Road is set around two new communal gardens that face Regents canal.

name: Wimbledon architecture walk
description: A 4-mile outdoor walking tour taking in a variety of Wimbledon's greater and lesser known buildings, led by Ramblers group, the Metropolitan Walkers. Includes urban areas (eg Wimbledon Village), plus the Windmill and Common.

name: Workable
description: Situated within the Rogers Stirk Harbour + Partners designed buildings at IQL, Workable is a new approach to flexible working in Stratford that combines panoramic views over London with stylish interior design.

name: Working Men's College
description: Outstanding Edwardian building (1905 grade II; many original features). The oldest UK adult college, founded 1854 by FD Maurice, John Ruskin & Christian Socialists. Purpose-designed by WD Caroe; updated for modern educational aspirations.

name: Wrotham Park
description: A privately-owned Grade II listed Palladian mansion with grand interiors restored in 1883, set in 300 acres of parkland in the midst of 2,500 acres. Built for Admiral The Hon. John Byng.

name: York House
description: Mid-17C house, a scheduled ancient monument, with fine staircase and 18C additions.

name: Yorkton Workshops
description: Pearson Lloyd have transformed a series of dilapidated workshop buildings into a new home for the studio. Original features have been retained and, wherever possible, the building’s constituent materials have been reused and recycled.
